<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: It's going to be a problem, possible solutions</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Hawthorne">Hawthorne</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 10:40 p.m. 11/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: It's going to be a problem, possible solutions<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=784" TARGET=_self>It's going to be a problem, possible solutions</A> (TheBlack[BCK])
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> #1 When you die, the player that killed you (or group) can loot

<BR>&gt; one item. All remaining items appear on your body when you
<BR>&gt; ressurect (advantage of being PvP).
<P>I think that should seriously be looked at. Lets face it. How can you help build a PvP community if people continually design games to discourage it in a role-playing fantasy setting. Being +PvP there are some things that are without a doubt. The most obvious is death. We all know all to well how difficult at times it can be to gain items and experience. its a given that you will lose BOTH experience and an item when you die. Why not a little encouragment?
<P>-Hawthorne, <a href="http://www.theregulators.org">The Regulators.</a>
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
